President Uhuru Kenyatta and a US delegation discussed ways of boosting trade and investments at State House in Nairobi on Friday. Gil Kaplan, the US Under Secretary of Commerce for International Trade, led the foreign team. The parties discussed how to share information between Kenyan and US companies. The meeting was timely as a Kenyan trade delegation is preparing to visit the US for promotional meetings and roadshows. They will present Kenya as the preferred destination for US investments on the continent. The visit will coincide with the Kenya Airways' first direct flight to the US in October. Read: US in 15 hours: KQ's maiden New York flight to cost Sh89,000 The meeting also discussed the construction of Kenya’s first high-speed expressway from Mombasa to Nairobi, by US engineering and construction company Bechtel. Uhuru and the US delegation resolved to firm up details of the expressway when the Kenyan team visits the US. The expressway is expected to be one of the most important new infrastructure projects in the East Africa. The President pledged government commitment to de-risking projects to ensure they are timely and withing budgets. An MOU to be signed between the governments of Kenya and the US, to facilitate infrastructure and the Big Four Agenda projects,. also featured in the talks. The meeting came after the two countries signed deals worth Sh10 billion at the Kenya-US trade conference at the UN Complex in Gigiri. Details: Kenya signs deals worth Sh10 billion with US, Big Four top agenda Click here for the latest political news